<p style="text-align: justify;">The surgical NGO map was created in partnership with the LCoGS and the PGSSC. In brief, a systematic search to identify relevant surgical organizations was done with the following methodology:</p>

<b>Who we included:</b>
<ol>
<li>NGOs who satisfied the UN Rule of Law definition: “a not-for- profit group, principally independent from government, which is organized on a local, national, or international level to address issues in support of a public good, ” </li>
<li>Provided surgery in one or more LMICs. Surgery was defined as the therapeutic excision, incision, or manipulation of tissue in an operating room, and was distinguished from the logistical or financial support of such care. This highly restrictive definition was chosen to facilitate a review of several large databases. LMICs were defined according to World Bank income groups, and included low-income, lower-middle income, and upper-middle income countries. </li>
</ol>

<b>Who we excluded:</b>
<ol>
<li>Organizations that exclusively transported patients to high-income countries for surgical procedures</li>
<li>Organizations that lack sufficient publicly available data on the web (in the form of mission statements, reports, trip schedules, photos, or testimonials) to confirm inclusion criteria.</li>
<li>CSOs with multiple national or regional branches (such as Médecins Sans Frontières, the International Committee of the Red Cross, and Médecins du Monde) were counted only once, under the name of the parent organization.</li>
</ol>

<b>The Search</b>

<p style="text-align: justify;">Our search was conducted in two rounds. The first round was designed to identify candidate organizations from databases of non-governmental organizations, from a review of the literature, and from social media. In the second round, we studied each organization’s website to confirm that the organization met inclusion criteria and to extract data.</p>

